# Command temu

## What does this command do:

TinyEMU is a system emulator for the RISC-V and x86 architectures. Its purpose is to be small and simple while being complete.

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: sudo dnf install openssl-devel libcurl-devel SDL-devel && git clone https://github.com/dearchap/tinyemu ~/Projects/3rd-party-repos/tinyemu && cd ~/Projects/3rd-party-repos/tinyemu && make && cp temu ~/.local/bin/ && chmod +x ~/.local/bin/temu
For Raspberry Pi install using: sudo apt install libssl-dev libcurl4-openssl-dev libsdl1.2-dev && git clone https://github.com/dearchap/tinyemu && cd tinyemu && make && cp temu ~/.local/bin/ && chmod +x ~/.local/bin/temu
For Mac install using: brew install --HEAD fernandotcl/fernandotcl/tinyemu  # dearchap/tinyemu does not build on macOS (uses Linux-only <byteswap.h>); fernandotcl's fork has macOS support (__APPLE__ guards, SDL2)

## Command path

For Fedora run: ~/.local/bin/temu
For Raspberry Pi run: ~/.local/bin/temu
For Mac run: /opt/homebrew/bin/temu

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://github.com/dearchap/tinyemu

## Command options

temu [options] config_file

-m ram_size    set the RAM size in MB
-rw            allow write access to disk image (default is snapshot/read-only)
-ctrlc         C-c stops the emulator instead of being sent to guest
-append        append string to kernel command line
-no-accel      disable KVM acceleration (x86 only)

Console keys:
  C-a x   exit the emulator
  C-a h   show console help

## Examples

# Run a remote RISC-V Linux image (no download needed)
temu https://bellard.org/jslinux/buildroot-riscv64.cfg

# Run a remote x86 image with SDL graphical display
temu https://bellard.org/jslinux/buildroot-x86-xwin.cfg

# Run a local config file
temu root-riscv64.cfg

# Run with 256 MB RAM and write access to disk
temu -m 256 -rw root-riscv64.cfg

# Run x86 without KVM acceleration
temu -no-accel my-x86.cfg

# Mount host /tmp into guest via 9P (add to config, then in guest):
# mount -t 9p /dev/root /mnt
